            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><font size="-1">quote:</font><HR>Originally posted by Carioca_FL:<BR><BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><font size="-1">quote:</font><HR>Originally posted by GodFather:<BR>...fairly common knowledge among hardware geeks ...<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><BR>I like to think I'm way more than a tinkerer, but I was never successful in swapping mobos, be it under 9x or NT -don't even ask me about Linux, I haven't gotten my feet wet on that one, yet. <img src="http://arstechnica.infopop.net/infopop/emoticons/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" width="15" height="15"><!--graemlin::)--><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><BR><BR>With linux it largely depends upon the distro.<BR>With a recent version of Red Hat (I think 6 or newer) as long as you have kudzo enabled - you just do your swap. It will detect that certain devices have been removed, detect that new ones have been added, and let you configure them.<BR><BR>With RH8 (7.3?) they started including some packages, like the kernel, optimized for your particular hardware. I think an Athlon optimized kernel would boot on a P4 just fine - but I'm not sure, never tried. But it would be a good idea to replace any cpu specific optimized packages if in that situation.<BR><BR>I don't know how well other distro's change a hardware swap. I've done it plenty of times w/ RH but never with Debian or SuSE or others.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
